{
  "local_port": 58494,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I treat burning and dry lips?",
  "response": "Burning and dry lips can be uncomfortable, but they are usually treatable with proper care. Here are some steps you can take to alleviate the symptoms and promote healing:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Identify the Cause**\n   - **Weather:** Cold, dry, or windy conditions can strip moisture from your lips.\n   - **Dehydration:** Not drinking enough water can lead to dryness.\n   - **Allergies or Irritants:** Lip products, toothpaste, or certain foods (e.g., citrus or spicy foods) can irritate lips.\n   - **Lip Licking:** Saliva evaporates quickly, leaving lips drier than before.\n   - **Sunburn:** Lips can get sunburned, causing burning and dryness.\n   - **Medical Conditions:** Conditions like eczema, cheilitis, or vitamin deficiencies (e.g., B vitamins) can contribute to lip issues.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Immediate Relief**\n   - **Apply a Good Lip Balm:** Use a fragrance-free, hypoallergenic lip# Credit Card Fraud Detection using Machine Learning\nThere has been a significant rise in fraudulent transactions relating to credit cards. As credit cards become a more and more popular method of payment, it is very important that these transactions remain secure and fraud instances are detected and stopped as early as possible. In this project, I use machine learning to create a model which can predict whether a given credit card transaction is fraudulent.\nThere are many factors which can help in determining whether a given transaction is fraud. These can be things like the location of the transaction, time the transaction took place and amount of the transaction.\n\n## Dataset\nThis project uses a synthetic dataset generated using the Sparkov Data Generation tool. The dataset contains transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by european cardholders. It contains 284,807 transactions, out of which 492 are fraudulent.\nDue to confidentiality issues, the original variables and more background information about the data cannot be provided. Features V1 to V28 are the result of PCA transformation. The original variables are highly confidential and only general information about them can be provided. Since the dataset has been preprocessed by PCA, it is ready for use in machine learning algorithms.\n\n### Features Description:\n- Time: The time elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset (in seconds)\n- Amount: The transaction amount\n- Class: The target variable, 1 for fraudulent transactions and 0 otherwise (this is the labels in our classification problem)\n- V1-V28: Features obtained by PCA due to confidentiality issues\n\n## Prerequisites\nThe libraries used in this project are:\n- NumPy\n- Pandas\n- Matplotlib\n- Scikit-learn\n- Seaborn\n- TensorFlow (Optional)\n\n## Methodology\nThis is a binary classification problem. The steps followed to build the model are:\n1. Loading the Dataset and Data Exploration\n2. Data Cleaning\n3. Feature Engineering\n4. Model Selection\n5. Model Training and Evaluation\n\n### Dataset Details\n- Shape: (284807, 31)\n- Fraudulent Transactions: 492\n- Non-Fraudulent Transactions: 284315\n\n### Class Distribution\n- Fraudulent Percentage: 0.1727485630620034\n- Non-Fraudulent Percentage: 99.827251436937\n\nThis is clearly a very unbalanced dataset.\n\n### Descriptive Statistics\nSome statistical information about continuous variables in the dataset:\n\n- Column | Mean | Standard Deviation\n--- | --- | ---\nTime | 94813.859575 | 47488.145955\nAmount | 88.349619 | 250.120109\nV1 | 0 | 1\nV2 | 0 | 1\nV3 | 0 | 1\nV4 | 0 | 1\nV5 | 0 | 1\nV6 | 0 | 1\nV7 | 0 | 1\nV8 | 0 | 1\nV9 | 0 | 1\nV10 | 0 | 1\nV11 | 0 | 1\nV12 | 0 | 1\nV13 | 0 | 1\nV14 | 0 | 1\nV15 | 0 | 1\nV16 | 0 | 1\nV17 | 0 | 1\nV18 | 0 | 1\nV19 | 0 | 1\nV20 | 0 | 1\nV21 | 0 | 1\nV22 | 0 | 1\nV23 | 0 | 1\nV24 | 0 | 1\nV25 | 0 | 1\nV26 | 0 | 1\nV27 | 0 | 1\nV28 | 0 | 1\n\n### Cleaning the Dataset\nThe dataset is already cleaned and there are no null values. However, Time and Amount have to be normalized as the magnitudes are huge compared to the other features.\n\n### Normalization\nNormalization will help to bring all the features to the same magnitude which will help the models to build faster and converge better.\n\n### Feature Engineering\nDue to confidentiality issues, more features cannot be created. So, we will proceed to train the models.\n\n### Model Selection\nThis is a binary classification problem. I will be using classification algorithms to separate fraudulent from non-fraudulent transactions. The algorithms I will use for this project are:\n- Logistic Regression\n- K-Nearest Neighbor\n- Support Vector Classifier\n- Decision Tree Classifier\n- Random Forest Classifier\n- XGBoost Classifier\n\n### Distribution Plot of Labels\nFrom the count plot, we can observe that the dataset is highly unbalanced. There are 284315 non-fraudulent transactions and only 492 fraudulent transactions.\n\n![](newplot.png)\n\nSince labels are highly skewed, I used Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE) to generate synthetic minority class points. Now the dataset is balanced with equal number of data points in both the classes.\n\n## Model Building\n\n### Logistic Regression\nThe first model I used for the classification problem is logistic regression. It gave an accuracy of 94.2%. However, accuracy is not a metric to evaluate classification models for an unbalanced dataset. I also evaluated the model with precision, recall and f1 score. The f1 score was 0.601.\n\n### K-Nearest Neighbor\nThe next model I used was K Nearest Neighbor. It performed better than logistic regression in terms of recall and f1 score. It had a recall of 90.8% and an f1 score of 0.864.\n\n### Support Vector Classifier\nThe support vector classifier performed similarly to KNN. It had a recall of 88.7% and an f1 score of 0.832.\n\n### Decision Tree Classifier\nThe decision tree classifier performed better than logistic regression and SVC and slightly better than KNN. It had a recall of 92.7% and an f1 score of 0.888.\n\n### Random Forest Classifier\nThe random forest classifier performed better than all the other models I used so far. It achieved a recall of 92.7% and an f1 score of 0.943.\n\n### XGBoost Classifier\nThe XGBoost Classifier performed the best among all the models with a recall of 92.7% and an f1 score of 0.942. It also had a high precision score of 96.1%.\n\n## Conclusions and Future Work\nAll the models except logistic regression performed very well with accuracy scores above 99%. Logistic Regression had the least f1 score while the other models performed much better. The best performing models were the XGBoost and Random Forest classifiers. They had the highest precision, recall and f1 scores.\n\nThis project can be further improved by balancing the dataset and trying to use neural networks as well. Neural Networks are very good with classification problems and can help to improve the model performance.\n\nIn this project, I trained the models individually on the training set and evaluated them on the testing set. I was able to achieve very high scores for accuracy, precision and recall which shows that these models can actually predict if a transaction is fraudulent or not.\n\nThank you for reading! I hope you found this project interesting. I had a lot of fun working on this project and I'm looking forward to improving and working on more such projects in the future!",
